        "number": 3,
        "title": "Exulting on their beds — the totality of praise and its eschatological horizon",
        "range": "149:5",
        "excerpt": "Let the godly ones exult in glory; let them sing for joy on their beds.",
        "body": "Verse 5 is the psalm's pivot, and its two halves span the whole range of the community's life. 'Let the godly ones exult in glory (kavod)' reaches back to verse 4's theological claim — the glory they exult in is the glory God has given in salvation, the kavod of being adorned by the LORD Himself. This is not self-congratulation; it is the overflow of received grace. The verb alaz (exult) describes a jubilant, even triumphant joy — the kind that erupts when a long-hoped-for reversal arrives.\n\nThe second half names the location: 'Let them sing for joy on their beds (mishkav).' This is the psalm's most intimate image. The mishkav is the private space — the couch or sleeping place where the day's public performance is over and the person is simply themselves. Praise on the beds has a long Psalter history: Psalm 63:6 ('I remember You on my bed; I meditate on You in the night watches'), Psalm 4:4 ('meditate in your heart upon your bed'). The point is the totality of the godly one's orientation toward God — neither public assembly nor private midnight is outside the scope of covenantal praise.\n\nThere is also an eschatological undertone in the juxtaposition of verse 5 with verses 6-9. The community that rests in God's glory on their beds while their enemies' kings are in chains is the community that has learned to trust the written judgment to God. They do not have to be anxious even in the vulnerability of sleep — the LORD who takes pleasure in them is executing His purposes. This is the same posture Psalm 4:8 describes: 'In peace I will both lie down and sleep, for You alone, O LORD, make me dwell in safety.'\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kavod* (glory) — weightiness, honor, splendor; the dominant word for God's own glory throughout the Psalter; here it is the glory the chasidim have been given by the God who adorns. *Alaz* (exult) — a verb of jubilant triumph, not quiet contentment. *Mishkav* (beds) — private sleeping space; the opposite spatial pole from the qahal of v.1."
