        "number": 4,
        "title": "Praise and sword — the worshiper's double commission",
        "range": "149:6-9",
        "excerpt": "Let the high praises of God be in their mouth, and a two-edged sword in their hand, to execute vengeance on the nations and punishment on the peoples.",
        "body": "The psalm's second movement (vv. 6-9) has generated more interpretive controversy than any other section of the Final Hallel. The transition from exulting saints on their beds to those same saints holding swords is abrupt and intentional — the psalm refuses to soften it. The waw conjunction in verse 6 ('and') places both elements in the same sentence, belonging to the same person, as simultaneous realities: high praises of God in the mouth and a two-edged sword in the hand. The worshiper is not first a worshiper and then a warrior; the psalm presents both as a single vocation.\n\nThree exegetical observations are essential. First, the sword's character: cherev peyot ('sword of mouths' — a blade with two cutting edges) appears elsewhere in the OT as a weapon of decisive, comprehensive judgment (Judg. 3:16; Prov. 5:4). In the NT, the same image is applied to the Word of God (Heb. 4:12: 'the word of God is living and active and sharper than any two-edged sword') and to the returning Christ (Rev. 1:16; 19:15: 'from His mouth came a sharp two-edged sword'). The canonical trajectory does not allow Christian readers to read this image in isolation from its NT realization. Second, the commission's scope: verses 7-8 describe the binding of kings and nobles — language that exceeds any historical military engagement of Israel and reads more naturally as eschatological imagery (cf. Rev. 20:1-3). Third, the warrant: verse 9 specifies that what the chasidim execute is 'the judgment written' — a judicial decree already on the divine record. They are not imposing their own agenda but carrying out a sentence that precedes them.\n\nReformed and dispensationalist scholars have agreed that the direct theocratic referent of the psalm is Israel's covenantal holy war vocation in the OT era. Both camps equally agree that Christian application requires the canonical lens of the NT: the sword is reidentified as the Word of God and the proclamation of the gospel (Eph. 6:17; Rev. 19:11-16). The church that praises in public assembly and on its beds, that holds high praises of God in its mouth — that community is already wielding the double-edged sword. The nations' kings are not brought into the chains of iron by military conquest; they are brought to the obedience of faith (Rom. 1:5; 16:26) by the proclaimed word that the Spirit blesses.\n\nThe closing declaration of verse 9 — 'This is an honor (hadar) for all His godly ones' — reverses any reading of the commission as burden or obligation. Participating in God's purposes in history, bearing the word that executes His written judgment, sharing in the eschatological vindication of the afflicted against every power that has pressed them down: this is the dignity conferred on the chasidim. The same God whose pleasure adorns the afflicted with yeshuah (v.4) now calls the participation in His judgment their hadar.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Romam el* (high praises of God) — literally 'exaltings of God,' the raised-high praise that belongs to the Most High. *Cherev peyot* (two-edged sword) — 'sword of mouths,' both edges cutting; the precise image Hebrews 4:12 and Revelation 19:15 apply to the word of God and to Christ. *Neqamah* (vengeance) — covenantal retribution, not private revenge; belongs first to God (Deut. 32:35). *Hadar* (honor) — the same word used of the splendor of God's majesty (Ps. 104:1; 111:3); what the chasidim receive is a share in the divine dignity."
